  <static seed="1319" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions2.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{7z}}}{{\frac{x}{7yz}}}=}</m><fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>y^{3}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{7z}}}{{\frac{x}{7yz}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{xy^{2}}{7z}}</m> and <m>{\frac{x}{7yz}}</m>, which is <m>{7yz}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{7z}}}{{\frac{x}{7yz}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{7z}}\cdot{7yz}}{{\frac{x}{7yz}}\cdot{7yz}} \\
    \amp = {y^{3}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Note that you are not required to enter lost domain conditions in this problem, but it<rsq/>s good to know the following.</p>
<p>Since <m>y</m> and <m>z</m> were canceled, <m>y \ne 0</m> and <m>z \ne 0</m> are in the lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
